## 4. Backend — Node.js / Express on Railway

### Architecture
It's a **single-file monolith** — all 269 lines of API logic live in [server.js](file:///d:/Desktop/projectx/modrn/backend/server.js). There are no separate route files, controllers, or middleware layers. Simple, but it works.

### Dependencies ([package.json](file:///d:/Desktop/projectx/modrn/backend/package.json))
| Package | Why |
|---|---|
| `express ^5.2.1` | Web framework / routing |
| `pg ^8.20.0` | PostgreSQL client (node-postgres) |
| `bcryptjs ^3.0.3` | Password hashing (salt rounds: 10) |
| `jsonwebtoken ^9.0.3` | JWT auth tokens (7-day expiry) |
| `cors ^2.8.6` | Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (allows `*` — any origin) |
| `dotenv ^17.4.2` | Loads `.env` variables |

### API Endpoints

#### Auth Routes
| Method | Endpoint | What It Does |
|---|---|---|
| `POST` | `/register` | Creates a user (hashes password, role = `'user'`) |
| `POST` | `/login` | Validates credentials, returns JWT + user `{id, name, role}` |
| `DELETE` | `/user/:id` | Deletes a user account |

#### Product Routes
| Method | Endpoint | What It Does |
|---|---|---|
| `GET` | `/products` | Fetches all products; supports `?search=` and `?category=` query params (ILIKE for case-insensitive search) |
| `POST` | `/products` | Creates a new product |
| `PUT` | `/products/:id` | Updates an existing product |
| `DELETE` | `/products/:id` | Deletes a product |

#### Order Routes
| Method | Endpoint | What It Does |
|---|---|---|
| `POST` | `/orders` | Places an order — inserts into `orders` + `order_items`, **decrements stock** per item |
| `GET` | `/orders/user/:user_id` | Fetches a specific user's order history |
| `GET` | `/orders` | Fetches ALL orders (admin) — LEFT JOIN with users for customer name |
| `PUT` | `/orders/:id/status` | Updates order status (Pending/Processing/Shipping/Delivered) |

> [!WARNING]
> **No auth middleware on admin routes.** Any endpoint (`POST /products`, `DELETE /products/:id`, `GET /orders`) can be called by anyone who knows the URL — there's no JWT verification middleware protecting these routes. The frontend does a client-side role check (`if user.role !== 'admin' → redirect`), but this is bypassable via DevTools or curl.

